My Dear Ward. I seem to be under a kind of spell when you propose anything. I am engaged on Wednesday—with my new book<note><hi rend="italic">Bleak House</hi> (No. I published 28 Feb).</note> in the day, and to dine at Bayswater with Egg the Painter,<note>Augustus Leopold Egg (1816-63; <hi rend="italic">Dictionary of National Biography</hi>), artist: see Pilgrim Letters 5, p. 113n.</note> in the evening. But I will get my Sub Editor Mr. Wills to see the invention<note>Not identified. Ward was particularly concerned with drainage for London and supported Sir Joseph Bazalgette: see Stephen Halliday, <hi rend="italic">The Great Stink of London: Sir Joseph Bazalgette and the Cleansing of the Victorian Metropolis</hi>, Stroud, Glos, 1999.</note> with a view to some account of it in Household Words,<note>No account of Ward or his invention appears in Household Words during the next year, though articles by Henry Morley (“A Foe under Foot”, <hi rend="italic">Household Words</hi>, 11 Dec 52, VI, 289-92) and by Wills (“Clear Water and Dirty Water”, <hi rend="italic">Household Words</hi>, 5 Feb 53, VI, 496-7) both concern sanitation.</note> and (as he knows Chadwick)<note>Edwin Chadwick (1800-90; <hi rend="italic">Dictionary of National Biography</hi>), social reformer. CD supported his efforts for sanitary reform.</note> will propose to him to be at the Board of Health<note>The General Board of Health, established 1848, with Chadwick as Chairman; its statutory life ended, July 54. The new Board, established Aug 54, was chaired by Benjamin Hall (Pilgrim <hi rend="italic">Letters</hi> 7, pp. 384<hi rend="italic">nn</hi>, 400<hi rend="italic">nn</hi>).</note> at the hour you appoint. 
